                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>Prime Minister Sidney G. Holland of New Zealand visited Washington February 5–10,
                    1951.</p>
                <p>Telegram 149 to Wellington, February 10, was a summary of talks held during the
                    Prime Minister’s visit. In it the Department stated in part:</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“In discussion [of a Japanese peace] treaty, Rusk indicated difficulties
                        which Holland understood: onus on US if responsible for policing
                        restrictions Jap rearmament, also Commie bid Jap support in such event,
                        present Jap disarmament sentiment, difficulty US indefinitely committing
                        forces defend Jap view obvious ability contribute own defense.</p>
                    <p>“Holland indicated problems security, non-restrictive Jap treaty more acute
                        Aus where strong polit issue, contrast NZ,” (694.001/2–1051)</p>
                </quote>
            </div>
        </body>
